Usage as a given name probably began in honour of the family, a notable member of which was a saint.
From the Old Norse name Þórsteinn, which meant "Thor's stone" from the name of the Norse god Þórr (see THOR) combined with steinn "stone".
From the Old Norse name Þórvaldr, which meant "Thor's ruler" from the name of the Norse god Þórr (see THOR) combined with valdr "ruler".
TOUFIK   m   ArabicVariant transcription of TAWFIQ.
form of the Old Norse name Tófa, a short form of ÞÓRFRÍÐR.
form of TOBIAH, also used as a feminine form.
TOYA   f   American (Hispanic)Diminutive of VICTORIA or CUSTODIA used among Hispanic Americans.
From a surname which was derived from a place name meaning "fishtrap ford" in Old English.

From the Roman cognomen Traianus, which is of unknown meaning. The Roman emperor Trajan (full name Marcus Ulpius Traianus) is considered among the most capable men to have led the empire. His military accomplishments include victories over Dacia and Parthia.
TRAUDL   f   GermanDiminutive of GERTRAUD or WALTRAUD.
means "strength" in Irish Gaelic. It is also sometimes used as an Irish form of THERESA.
From the English word, ultimately from Greek θησαυρος (thesauros) "treasure, collection".
From a surname which originally denoted someone who lived by the River Trent in England. Trent is also a city in Italy, though the etymology is unrelated.
From a surname which was derived from a Cornish place name meaning "homestead on the hill".
short form of DEMETRIA and other names ending in a similar sound.
TRIJNTJE   f   DutchDutch diminutive of KATRIJN.
Means "trinity" in Spanish, referring to the Holy Trinity. An island in the West Indies bears this name.
Variant of TRISTAN, sometimes used as a feminine form.
From the Old Norse byname Þróndr which indicated a person from Trøndelag, a region in central Norway, possibly derived from þróast meaning "to grow, to prosper".
TRUDI   f   German, EnglishDiminutive of GERTRUDE and other Germanic names ending with the element thrud "strength".
TRUDY   f   English, DutchDiminutive of GERTRUDE.
Derived from Old Norse tryggr meaning "trustworthy".
From the Greek name Τρυφαινα (Tryphaina), derived from Greek τρυφη (tryphe) meaning "softness, delicacy". This name is mentioned briefly in the New Testament.
Derived from Greek τρυφη (tryphe) meaning "softness, delicacy". In the New Testament this name is mentioned briefly as belonging to a companion of Tryphena.
TSERING   m & f   TibetanVariant transcription of TSHERING.
derived from Georgian ცის (tsis) meaning "of the sky", the genitive case of ცა (tsa) "sky, heaven".
Means "heavenly, celestial" in Georgian, a derivative of ცა (tsa) "sky, heaven".
From Japanese 燕 (tsubame) meaning "swallow (bird)" or other kanji which have the same pronunciation.
From Japanese 月 (tsuki) meaning "moon" and 子 (ko) meaning "child". Other combinations of kanji are possible.
Derived from Bulgarian цвет (tsvet) meaning "flower, blossom".
From Sino-Vietnamese 秀 (tú) meaning "luxuriant, beautiful, elegant, outstanding".
Means "ruler of the people" in Irish Gaelic.
From an occupational surname derived from Old English tucian meaning "one who fulls cloth".

Means "image of the life of Amon", derived from Egyptian tut "image" combined with ankh "life" combined with the name of the god Amon. This was the name of an Egyptian pharaoh of the 18th dynasty, most famous because of the treasures found in his tomb.
TUUKKA   m   FinnishFinnish diminutive of TUURE.
Means "little wind" in Finnish, derived from tuuli "wind". This was the name of a Finnish forest goddess, the daughter of Tapio.
from a Cajun pronunciation of French étoile "star". It came into use as an American given name in the late 19th century.
Short form of TYLER, TYSON, TYRONE, and other names beginning with Ty.
From the Greek name Τυχων (Tychon) meaning "hitting the mark". This was the name of a Greek saint. It was also borne by the Danish astronomer Tycho Brahe (1546-1601).
From a surname meaning "pasture" in Middle English.

form of the name of the Germanic god Tiwaz, related to Indo-European dyeus (see ZEUS). In Norse mythology Tyr was the god of war and justice, the son of the god Odin. He carried a spear in his left hand, since his right hand was bitten off by the wolf Fenrir. At the time of the end of the world, the Ragnarok, Tyr will slay and be slain by the giant hound Garm.
TYRIQ   m   African American (Modern)Probably a blend of TYRONE and TARIQ.

From the name of a county in Northern Ireland which is derived from Irish Gaelic Tir Eoghain meaning "land of EOGHAN". This name was popularized by American actor Tyrone Power (1914-1958), who was named after his great-grandfather, an Irish actor.

From an English surname which could be derived from a nickname for a quarrelsome person, from Old French tison meaning "firebrand". Alternatively, it could be a variant of DYSON. A famous bearer of the surname was boxer Mike Tyson (1966-).
TZIPORA   f   HebrewVariant transcription of TZIPPORAH.
UELI   m   German (Swiss)Swiss diminutive of ULRICH.
form of the Old Norse name HUGLEIKR, or else a diminutive of UILLIAM.
form of the Old Norse name EYSTEINN.

From Sino-Korean 宇 (u) meaning "house, eaves, universe" or 佑 (u) meaning "help, protect, bless" combined with 眞 (jin) meaning "real, genuine" or 鎭 (jin) meaning "town, market place". Other combinations of hanja characters can form this name as well.
Means "old man" in Finnish. In Finnish mythology Ukko is the god of the sky and thunder.
From the Old Norse byname Úlfr meaning "wolf".
ULIANA   f   RussianVariant transcription of ULYANA.
ULLA   f   Swedish, Danish, Norwegian, Finnish, GermanScandinavian diminutive of ULRIKA or HULDA  (1), or a German diminutive of URSULA.
ULLI   m & f   GermanDiminutive of ULRICH or ULRIKE.
form of the Old English name Wulfric meaning "wolf power". When it is used in modern times, it is usually as a variant of ULRICH.

From the Germanic name Odalric meaning "prosperity and power", from the element odal "heritage" combined with ric "power". It has long been confused with the Germanic name Hulderic. This was the name of two German saints. Another famous bearer was Ulrich Zwingli (1484-1531), also known as Huldrych, the leader of the Protestant Reformation in Switzerland.
Means "of Ulster" in Gaelic. Ulster is a region in the north of Ireland. This name was borne by two 7th-century Irish saints.

form of ODYSSEUS. It was borne by Ulysses S. Grant (1822-1885), the commander of the Union forces during the American Civil War, who went on to become an American president. Irish author James Joyce used it as the title of his book 'Ulysses' (1920), which loosely parallels Homer's epic the 'Odyssey'.

Means "populous, flourishing", derived from Arabic عمر ('umr) "life". Umar was a companion and strong supporter of Muhammad who became the second caliph of the Muslims. He is considered to be one of the great founders of the Muslim state. The name was also borne by a 12th-century poet from Persia, Umar Khayyam.
From Japanese 梅 (ume) meaning "plum". In Japan the plum blossom is thought to symbolize devotion. Different kanji or kanji combinations can also form this name.
Means "hope" in Uzbek, ultimately from Persian امید (omid).
Means "hope" in Turkish, ultimately from Persian امید (omid).
Variant of ÜMİT. The Turkish words umut and ümit are etymologically related synonyms.
Means "God is with us" in Xhosa.
From the English word unity, which is ultimately derived from Latin unitas.
Derived from Old Norse unnr "to wave, to billow" or unna "to love".
From a surname which was derived from a place name meaning "upper town" in Old English. A famous bearer of this name was the American novelist Upton Sinclair (1878-1968).

From the Hebrew name אוּרִיָה ('Uriyah) which meant "YAHWEH is my light". In the Old Testament this is the name of a Hittite warrior in King David's army, the first husband of Bathsheba. David desired Bathsheba so he placed Uriah in the forefront of battle so he would be killed.
Means "privileged birth" from Celtic orbo "privileged" and gen "birth". In Welsh legend and Arthurian romances Urien is a king of Gore and the husband of Morgan le Fay.
UROS   m   SerbianVariant transcription of UROŠ.
form of the Latin name Ursus, which meant "bear". Saint Ursus was a 3rd-century soldier in the Theban Legion who was martyred with Saint Victor. He is the patron saint of Solothurn in Switzerland.
URSEL   f   GermanGerman diminutive of URSULA.
URSINUS   m   Late RomanLatin name which was a derivative of Ursus (see URS).

Means "little bear", derived from a diminutive form of the Latin word ursa "she-bear". Saint Ursula was a legendary virgin princess of the 4th century who was martyred by the Huns while returning from a pilgrimage. In England the saint was popular during the Middle Ages, and the name came into general use at that time.
origine: [English, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, German, Dutch, Finnish, Late Roman]
[Hinduism, Indian, Kannada, Tamil, Telugu, Malayalam, Hindi, Marathi, Nepali]

signification: From the Welsh name Uthyr, derived from Welsh uthr "terrible". In Arthurian legend Uther was the father of King Arthur. He appears in some early Welsh texts, but is chiefly known from the 12th-century chronicles of Geoffrey of Monmouth.
Derived from Sumerian ud meaning "sun". In Sumerian mythology this was the name of the god of the sun. He was the son of the moon god Nanna and Ningal.
Means "my power" in Hebrew. This is the name of several minor characters in the Old Testament.
Means "my power is God" in Hebrew. This is the name of several minor characters in the Old Testament.
form of BADEMUS, but it may actually be derived from the Slavic name VADIMIR or else from an Old Norse source.
From Avestan Verethragna meaning "breaking of defense, victory". In Armenian mythology this was the name of the heroic god of war.
Derived from Old Persian varka-tanu meaning "wolf-bodied". This name was borne by several kings of Georgia.
from Germanic wald meaning "power, rule". It has been in use only since the 20th century.
form of WALDEMAR. This was the name of four kings of Denmark.
Short form of VOLDEMĀRS and other Latvian names containing the Germanic/Baltic element wald "rule".
From the name of cities in Spain and Venezuela, both derived from Latin valentia meaning "strength, vigour".

From the Roman cognomen Valentinus which was itself from the name Valens meaning "strong, vigourous, healthy" in Latin. Saint Valentine was a 3rd-century martyr. His feast day was the same as the Roman fertility festival of Lupercalia, which resulted in the association between Valentine's day and love. As an English name, it has been used occasionally since the 12th century.
VALENTINIANUS   m   Ancient RomanRoman cognomen which was a derivative of the cognomen Valentinus (see VALENTINE  (1)). This name was borne by three Roman emperors.
form of VALERIUS, as well as a variant transcription of the Russian name VALERIY.
Feminine form of VALERIUS. This was the name of a 2nd-century Roman saint and martyr.

From the Roman cognomen Valerianus, which was itself derived from the Roman name VALERIUS. This was the name of a 3rd-century Roman emperor. Several saints also had this name, including a 2nd-century martyr of Lyons.
derived from Latin valere "to be strong". This was the name of several early saints.
Derived from the Germanic elements walha "foreign" and ric "power". It has been frequently confused with the name Valère.
Means "creeping plant" in Dravidian. In Dravidian mythology the goddess Valli was the wife of Murunga.
short form of VALDEMAR or other names containing vald.
Short form of names containing van, such as VANCE or IVAN.

VANESSA   f   English, Italian, Portuguese, German, DutchInvented by author Jonathan Swift for his poem 'Cadenus and Vanessa' (1726). He arrived at it by rearranging the initial syllables of the first name and surname of Esther Vanhomrigh, his close friend. Vanessa was later used as the name of a genus of butterfly. It was a rare given name until the mid-20th century, at which point it became fairly popular.
form of VANYA. It is also used in Scandinavia, where it is primarily feminine.
Means "golden" in Khmer, ultimately from Sanskrit.
VARDAH   f   HebrewVariant transcription of VARDA.
Derived from Georgian ვარდი (vardi) meaning "rose", ultimately from Persian via Armenian.
VARFOLOMEI   m   Russian (Rare)Variant transcription of VARFOLOMEY.
VARIUS   m   Ancient RomanRoman family name which meant "versatile" in Latin. Varius Rufus was a Roman epic poet of the 1st century BC.
From the Finnish name for a type of berry bush.
VARTAN   m   ArmenianVariant transcription of VARDAN.
VARTOUHI   f   ArmenianVariant transcription of VARDUHI.
Means "brilliant" or "spring" in Sanskrit. This is the name of a Hindu personification of the spring.

From the medieval Spanish name Velasco which possibly meant "crow" in Basque. A famous bearer was the 15th-century Portuguese explorer Vasco da Gama, the first person to sail from Europe around Africa to India.
VASILI   m   RussianVariant transcription of VASILIY.
VASILY   m   RussianVariant transcription of VASILIY.
VASKO   m   Macedonian, BulgarianDiminutive of VASIL.
VASSILIS   m   GreekVariant transcription of VASILIS.
Means "bright, excellent" in Sanskrit. This is an epithet of several Hindu gods. It also belonged to one of the authors of the Rigveda.
origine: [Hinduism, Indian, Kannada, Malayalam, Telugu, Tamil, Hindi]

signification: Means "producer of wealth" in Sanskrit, used to refer to the earth.
From a Welsh surname which was derived from Welsh bychan meaning "little".
Means "opportunity, good fortune, fate" in Khmer.
form of a Germanic or Celtic name, possibly Germanic WIDOGAST. This was the name of a 6th-century saint who helped to convert the Frankish king Clovis to Christianity.
Means "clear, cheerful" in Croatian and Serbian.
VEERKE   f   Dutch, LimburgishDiminutive of VEER.
VELDA   f   EnglishMeaning unknown, possibly a derivative of the Germanic element wald meaning "power, rule".
Derived from the Slavic elements veli "great" and borti "battle".
VELJKO   m   Serbian, CroatianDiminutive of VESELKO.
variant of WILMA, the spelling with an e perhaps due to the influence of SELMA. This name has been in use since the 19th century.
feminine form of ULRICH. This was the name of two queens of Sweden.

Means "flax" in Sanskrit. This is another name of the Hindu goddess Parvati. In Hindu texts it is said to derive from the Sanskrit exclamation उ मा (u ma) meaning "O (child), do not (practice austerities)!" which was addressed to Parvati by her mother.
origine: [Hinduism, Indian, Telugu, Kannada, Malayalam, Tamil, Hindi]

signification: form of HUMBERT. A famous bearer was Italian author Umberto Eco (1932-2016).
From Japanese 梅 (ume) meaning "plum" and 子 (ko) meaning "child". Other kanji combinations are possible.
Derived from Latin unda meaning "wave". The word undine was created by the medieval author Paracelsus, who used it for female water spirits.
From the English word unique, ultimately derived from Latin unicus.
From the name of the Ural Mountains, of uncertain meaning, possibly from Turkic aral meaning "island, boundary". This is the name of the title character in the Bashkir epic 'Ural-batyr'.

From Greek Ουρανος (Ouranos), the name of the husband of Gaia and the father of the Titans in Greek mythology. His name is derived from ουρανος (ouranos) meaning "the heavens". This is also the name of the seventh planet in the solar system.
From the Latin name Urbanus which meant "city dweller". This name is mentioned briefly in one of Paul's epistles in the New Testament. It was subsequently borne by eight popes.
origine: [Danish, Swedish, German, Polish, Slovene, Biblical, History]

signification: From the Old Norse Urðr meaning "fate". In Norse mythology Urd was one of the three Norns, or goddesses of destiny. She was responsible for the past.
Means "my light" in Hebrew. This was the name of the father of Bezalel in the Old Testament.

From the Hebrew name אוּרִיאֵל ('Uri'el) which meant "God is my light". Uriel was one of the seven archangels in Hebrew tradition. He is mentioned only in the Apocrypha, for example in the Book of Enoch where he warns Noah of the coming flood.
Form of URIAH used in some English versions of the Old Testament (for a character in the Book of Jeremiah).
form of an old Hungarian name, possibly from úr meaning "man, lord" combined with a diminutive suffix. This was the name of five Serbian kings.
Feminine form of URSUS. This is the name of two constellations in the northern sky: Ursa Major and Ursa Minor.
URŠKA   f   SloveneSlovene diminutive of URSULA.
URTĖ   f   LithuanianPossibly a Lithuanian diminutive of DOROTHY.
Means "rabbit" in Japanese. This name was used on the Japanese television show 'Sailor Moon'.
Means "dawn" in Sanskrit. This is the name of the Hindu goddess of the dawn, considered the daughter of heaven.
USMAN   m   ArabicVariant transcription of UTHMAN.
Means "baby bustard" in Arabic (a bustard is a type of large bird). Uthman was a companion of Muhammad who married two of his daughters. He was the third caliph of the Muslims.

Means "north" in Sanskrit. This is a transcription of both the masculine form उत्तर (also written Uttar) and the feminine form उत्तरा (also written Uttarā), both of which occur in the Hindu epic the 'Mahabharata' belonging to the son and daughter of King Virata.
From the Basque name of the Spanish town of Ujué where there is a church dedicated to the Virgin Mary. Its name is derived from Basque usoa "dove".
Means "my power is YAHWEH" in Hebrew. This is the name of several Old Testament characters including a king of Judah.

form of the older name Veceslav, from the Slavic elements veche "more" and slava "glory". Saint Václav (known as Wenceslas in English) was a 10th-century duke of Bohemia murdered by his brother. He is the patron saint of the Czech Republic. This was also the name of several Bohemian kings.
from the Slavic elements vaditi "accuse" and miru "peace, world".

Derived from Finnish väinä "wide and slow-flowing river". In Finnish mythology Väinämöinen was a wise old magician, the son of the primal goddess Ilmatar. He is the hero of the Finnish epic the 'Kalevala'.
Derived from the name of the Hindu god VISHNU, meaning "belonging to Vishnu". This is the name of one of the seven Matrika goddesses in Hinduism.
Short form of VALENTINE  (1), VALERIE, and other names beginning with Val.
Short form of VALDEMARAS and other Lithuanian names containing the Germanic/Baltic element wald "rule".
VALDEMARAS   m   LithuanianLithuanian cognate of WALDEMAR.
Derived from Old Norse valr "the dead" and dís "goddess".
From the English word meaning "wide river valley".
VALENS   m   Ancient RomanRoman cognomen (see VALENTINE  (1)). This name was borne by a 4th-century Roman emperor.

origine: [French, Romanian, German, Danish, Swedish, Norwegian, Czech, Russian, Bulgarian, Slovene, Croatian, Macedonian]

signification: Feminine form of Valentinus (see VALENTINE  (1)). A famous bearer was the Soviet cosmonaut Valentina Tereshkova (1937-), who in 1963 became the first woman to visit space.
origine: [Italian, Russian, Slovene, Croatian, Macedonian, Romanian, Spanish, Ancient Roman]

signification: form of VALERIA and Czech variant of VALÉRIE.
VALERY   m   RussianVariant transcription of VALERIY.
VALI   m   RomanianRomanian diminutive of VALERIU or VALENTIN.
Means "chooser of the slain", derived from Old Norse valr "the slain" and kyrja "chooser". In Norse myth the Valkyries were maidens who led heroes killed in battle to Valhalla.
VALTER   m   Portuguese, Italian, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Slovene, Croatian, EstonianCognate of WALTER.
origine: [Portuguese, Italian, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Slovene, Croatian, Estonian]

signification: From Sino-Vietnamese 文 (văn) meaning "literature, culture, writing". This is a common middle name for Vietnamese boys.
Short form of IVANA or JOVANA.
From an English surname which was derived from Old English fenn meaning "marsh, fen".
Derived from Armenian վարդ (vard) meaning "rose", ultimately from Persian.
from a Sanskrit word meaning "to surround". In Hindu mythology Varuna is a god of water and the celestial ocean surrounding the world. He is one of the chief gods in the Hindu text the Rigveda.
means "thread" in Hebrew, but it is most likely of Persian origin. In the Old Testament this is the name of the first wife of King Ahasuerus of Persia before he marries Esther.
VASILKA   f   Bulgarian, MacedonianBulgarian and Macedonian feminine diminutive of BASIL  (1).
VASKA   m & f   Russian, Macedonian, BulgarianRussian diminutive of VASILIY (masculine) or a Macedonian and Bulgarian diminutive of VASILIJA (feminine).
VASO   m   Greek, Georgian, SerbianDiminutive of VASILIS, VASIL or VASILIJE.
VASSILY   m   RussianVariant transcription of VASILIY.
Means "granting wealth" in Sanskrit. This is another name of the earth.
Means "possessor of wealth" in Sanskrit, used to refer to the earth.
From a surname which was a variant of VAUGHN.
Means "air, wind" in Sanskrit. This is the name of the Hindu god of the air and wind, one of the five elements.
VEETI   m   FinnishFinnish diminutive of FREDRIK or FERDINAND.
From the Roman family name Velius which possibly means "concealed" in Latin.
Derived from the Slavic elements veli "great" and miru "peace, world".
From Finnish velloa "to surge, to swell". This was the name of a Finnish goddess of the sea, the wife of Ahti.
Means "wolf" in Yiddish. This name can also be used as a Yiddish form of WILLIAM.

From the English word for the soft fabric. It became used as a given name after the main character in Enid Bagnold's book 'National Velvet' (1935) and the movie (1944) and television (1960) adaptations.
Derived from Sanskrit वेन (vena) meaning "yearning". This is the name of an evil king in Hindu mythology.
form of VÁCLAV, via the Latinized form Venceslaus.

form of GWYNEDD or GWYNETH. It also coincides with the name of the city in Italy, called Venice in English. This name was borne by the celebrated beauty Venetia Stanley (1600-1633). Benjamin Disraeli used it in his novel entitled 'Venetia' (1837).
From the name of a sacred hill in southern India.
form of VÁCLAV, via the Latinized form Venceslaus.
VENYAMIN   m   RussianVariant transcription of VENIAMIN.
From the Old Norse Verðandi meaning "becoming, happening". Verdandi was one of the three Norns, or goddesses of destiny, in Norse mythology. She was responsible for the present.
form of the Ptolemaic name BERENICE. Saint Verena was a 3rd-century Egyptian-born nurse who went with the Theban Legion to Switzerland. After the legion was massacred she settled near Zurich.
From the Latin name Verissimus which meant "very true". Saint Verissimus was a Portuguese martyr executed during the persecutions of the Roman emperor Diocletian in the early 4th century.
From the English word meaning "verity, truth". This was one of the virtue names adopted by the Puritans in the 17th century.
Feminine form of VERNON, sometimes associated with the Latin word vernus "spring". It has been in use since the 19th century.
From a Norman surname which was from a French place name, ultimately derived from the Gaulish word vern meaning "alder".
From the name of the city in Italy, which is itself of unknown meaning.
VERONIKA   f   Russian, Czech, Slovak, German, Hungarian, Bulgarian, Slovene, Croatian, Macedonian, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Lithuanian, LatvianCognate of VERONICA.
origine: [Russian, Czech, Slovak, German, Hungarian, Bulgarian, Slovene, Croatian, Macedonian, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Lithuanian, Latvian]

signification: VERTTI   m   FinnishFinnish diminutive of FERDINAND.
Derived from South Slavic vesel meaning "cheerful".
Derived from South Slavic vesel meaning "cheerful".

Means "messenger" in Slavic. This was the name of a Slavic spirit associated with the springtime. In many Slavic languages this is now the poetic word for "spring". It has been used as a given name only since the 20th century.
VESTA   f   Roman MythologyProbably a Roman cognate of HESTIA. Vesta was the Roman goddess of the hearth. A continuous fire, tended by the Vestal Virgins, was burned in the Temple of Vesta in Rome.
VIATOR   m   Late RomanLate Latin name (see BEATRIX). This was the name of a 4th-century Italian saint.
VIBIANUS   m   Ancient RomanRoman cognomen which was a derivative of VIBIUS.
Means "victory" in Latin, being borne by the Roman goddess of victory. It is also a feminine form of VICTORIUS. This name was borne by a 4th-century saint and martyr from North Africa.... [more]
origine: [English, Spanish, Romanian, German, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Late Roman, Roman Mythology]

signification: derived from VICTOR. This was the name of a ruler of the Gallic Empire in the 3rd century. It was also borne by the 4th-century Roman grammarian and philosopher Victorinus Afer as well as a few early saints.
feminine form of WIDO or VITUS.

From the Old Norse Víðarr, which is possibly derived from víðr "wide" and arr "warrior". In Norse mythology Víðarr was the son of Odin and Grid. At the time of the end of the world, the Ragnarok, he will avenge his father's death.
From the French name of the capital city of Austria, known in English as Vienna.
Derived from the Old Norse elements víg "war" and dís "goddess".
Short form of names containing the Old Norse element víg "war".

Means "victory" in Sanskrit. This is a transcription of both the masculine form विजय and the feminine form विजया, both of which are used frequently in Hindu texts. It is the name of a grandson of Indra, a son of Krishna and it is another name of the goddess Durga. This was also the name of a semi-legendary 6th-century BC king of Sri Lanka.
origine: [Hinduism, Indian, Telugu, Kannada, Tamil, Malayalam, Marathi, Hindi]

signification: From the Old Norse name Víkingr meaning "viking, raider", ultimately from vík "bay, inlet".
Means "stride, pace" or "valour" in Sanskrit. This is another name of the Hindu god Vishnu. This was also the name of a semi-legendary 1st-century BC king (full name Vikramaditya) of Ujjain in India.
variant of VICTORIA. It is also a variant transcription of VIKTORIYA.
origine: [German, Swedish, Norwegian, Danish, Estonian, Russian, Ukrainian, Bulgarian]

signification: VILLE   m   Finnish, SwedishFinnish and Swedish diminutive of WILLIAM.

origine: [Spanish, Portuguese, Finnish, German, Swedish, Hungarian, Czech, Slovak, Croatian]

signification: From the Baltic elements vil- "hope" and tauta "people, nation".
form of the Roman family name Vinicius, which was possibly derived from Latin vinum "wine".
VIOLANTE   f   Late RomanOlder form (possibly) of YOLANDA.

From the Roman family name Vergilius which is of unknown meaning. This name was borne by the 1st-century BC Roman poet Publius Vergilius Maro, commonly called Virgil, who was the writer of the 'Aeneid'. Due to him, Virgil has been in use as a given name in the English-speaking world since the 19th century.

Feminine form of the Roman family name Verginius or Virginius which is of unknown meaning, but long associated with Latin virgo "maid, virgin". According to a legend, it was the name of a Roman woman killed by her father so as to save her from the clutches of a crooked official.... [more]
origine: [English, Italian, Spanish, Portuguese, Swedish, Romanian, Ancient Roman]

signification: From the Latin name Viriathus or Viriatus, which was derived from viriae "bracelets" (of Celtic origin). Viriathus was a leader of the Lusitani (a tribe of Portugal) who rebelled against Roman rule in the 2nd century BC.

origine: [Indian, Hindi, Marathi, Gujarati, Punjabi, Telugu, Tamil, Kannada, Bengali]

signification: Means "visitation" in Spanish. This name is given in reference to the visit of the Virgin Mary to her cousin Elizabeth.
VISSARION   m   Russian, GreekRussian form and modern Greek transcription of BESSARION.
derived from the Baltic elements vis "all" and vald "rule". It is thus a cognate of the Slavic VSEVOLOD.
VITALI   m   Russian, UkrainianVariant transcription of VITALIY.
VITALIK   m   Russian, UkrainianDiminutive of VITALIY.
VITALY   m   Russian, UkrainianVariant transcription of VITALIY.
derived from Latin vita "life". Saint Vitus was a child martyred in Sicily in the early 4th century. From an early date this name was confused with the Germanic name Wido.

origine: [Indian, Hindi, Marathi, Gujarati, Tamil, Kannada, Telugu, Malayalam, Bengali]

signification: VIVI   f   Danish, Swedish, NorwegianScandinavian diminutive of names beginning with Vi, as well as OLIVIA and SOFIA.
Feminine form of Vivianus (see VIVIAN). Saint Viviana (also known as Bibiana) was a Roman saint and martyr of the 4th century.
Derived from the Slavic elements vyeku "age" and slava "glory".
VJERA   f   Croatian, SerbianCroatian and Serbian cognate of VERA  (1).
Short form of Slavic names beginning with the element vladeti meaning "rule".
Derived from the Slavic elements vladeti "rule" and slava "glory".
